{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Karcher v. May |ArgueDate=October 6 |ArgueYear=1987 |DecideDate=December 1 |DecideYear=1987 |FullName=Karcher, Speaker of the New Jersey General Assembly, et al. v. May et al |USVol=484 |USPage=72 |ParallelCitations=108 S. Ct. 388; 98 [[Lawyers' Edition|L. Ed. 2d]] 327; 1987 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 5027 |Prior= |Subsequent= |Holding= |Docket= 85-1551 |SCOTUS=1986-1987 |Majority=O'Connor |JoinMajority=Rehnquist, Brennan, Marshall, Blackmun, Stevens, Scalia |Concurrence=White |LawsApplied=[[Article Three of the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. Art. III]], [[Federal Rules of Appellate Procedure|Federal Rule of Appellate Procedure]] 43(c)(1) }}
'''''Karcher v. May''''', 484 U.S. 72 (1987),<ref name=decision>{{ussc|name=Karcher v. May|volume=484|page=72|pin=|year=1987}}.</ref> was a [[school prayer]] case in which the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] held that the former presiding officers of the New Jersey legislature did not have Article III [[standing (law)|standing]] to appeal a case, that standing had passed on to their legislative successors.
==Background== In 1982, the [[New Jersey]] [[New Jersey Legislature|Legislature]] passed a statute over the governor's veto providing for a [[moment of silence]] in public schools, which failed to specifically mention [[prayer]]. May filed a lawsuit in the federal [[United States District Court for the District of New Jersey]] challenging the constitutionality of the statute; the executive-branch officials normally tasked with defending such suits (the Governor and the Attorney General) admitted the unconstitutionality of the statute and refused to defend it in court. Consequently, [[Alan Karcher]], Speaker of the [[New Jersey General Assembly]], and [[Carmen Orechio]], President of the [[New Jersey Senate]], moved to [[intervention (law)|intervene]] (under Rule 24 of the [[Federal Rules of Civil Procedure]]) as defendants on behalf of the Legislature; the court granted the motion. In 1983, the District Court found that the purpose of the statute was religious, and deemed the law unconstitutional on [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] grounds.<ref name=kamen>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1357500.html|title=Ruling on `Moment of Silence' Avoided; Court Also Curtails Environmental Suits Under Clean Water Act|last=Kamen|first=Al|date=December 2, 1987|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1347183.html|title=Court Hears Suit Over Schools' Moment of Silence; Questions Suggest a Definitive Ruling Is Unlikely on New Jersey Law's Constitutionality|last=Kamen|first=Al|date=October 7, 1987|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>
Karcher and Orechio appealed, although by the time of filing their terms as Speaker and President had expired; their successors, [[Chuck Hardwick]] and [[John F. Russo]], joined the executive officers in refusing to defend the constitutionality of the statute. Karcher and Orechio's lawyer, [[Rex E. Lee]], nevertheless contended that their standing to continue to defend suit on the state's behalf remained, and also argued the purpose of the law was secular.<ref name="Association1987">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F3Kqlldz7GAC&pg=PA50|accessdate=20 December 2012|date=1987-10-01|publisher=American Bar Association Journal|pages=50–|title=School Prayer|author=Andrea Neal}}</ref><ref name="Vile2001">{{cite book|last=Vile|first=John R.|title=Great American Lawyers: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XR1NPiqp5aQC&pg=PA457|accessdate=20 December 2012|year=2001|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781576072028|pages=457–}}</ref>
==Opinion of the Court== The court found that the former legislative leaders lacked standing,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.edweek.org/ew/articles/1987/12/09/07390036.h07.html|title=Technicality Bars Ruling On Moments of Silence|last=Mirga|first=Tom|date=December 9, 1987|work=Education Week|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> but that that authority had passed by design to the current leaders of the New Jersey legislature.<ref name="Schwartz1995">{{cite book|last=Schwartz|first=|title=Section 1983 Lit: Clms V1b 3e|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5tmAUU_QtqQC&pg=PA178|accessdate=20 December 2012|date=1995-12-31|publisher=Aspen Publishers Online|isbn=9780735549357|pages=178–}}</ref> Justice [[Sandra Day O'Connor]]'s majority decision was joined by six other justices, with Justice [[Byron White]] writing a concurring opinion. There was no ninth vote, as Justice [[Lewis F. Powell, Jr.]] had resigned earlier in the year, and no replacement had yet been confirmed.
As a result of this opinion, the district court ruling that the law was unconstitutional was left intact.<ref name=kamen/>
